SIMPLE: isomer
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Isomer
<hw>I"so*mer</hw> <pr>(⟦imac⟧"s⟦osl⟧*m⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[See <er>Isomeric</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A compound
which is isomeric with another body or compound; a compound having the
same chemical composition as another compound; a member of an isomeric
series.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ An isomer may be a <altname>structural isomer</altname>,
in which some of the atoms are bonded to different atoms (as in
<chform>CH3.CH2.NH2</chform> and <chform>CH3.NH.CH3</chform>), or an
<altname>optical isomer</altname>, in which the number and types of
chemical bonds are identical, but the arrangement of the atoms in
three-dimensional space is different; the latter are also called
<altname>stereoisomers</altname>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Isomere</ent>⟦br⟧
